The '''List of Unicode radicals''' comprises those [[Unicode]] characters that represent [[Radical (Chinese character)|radical components]] of [[CJK characters]], [[Tangut (Unicode block)|Tangut characters]] or [[Yi Syllables (Unicode block)|Yi syllables]]. These are used primarily for indexing characters in dictionaries.
There are two CJK radicals blocks: the "Kangxi Radicals" block that includes the [[List of Kangxi radicals|214 standard radicals]] used in the ''[[Kangxi Dictionary]]''; and the "CJK Radicals Supplement" block that includes 115 radical components used in other modern dictionaries, including [[Simplified Chinese characters|simplified Chinese]] and [[Shinjitai|Japanese]] radicals forms.<ref>{{Cite book | title=The Unicode Standard Version 6.2 | url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode6.2.0/ch12.pdf | page=435 }}</ref>
There is one "Tangut Components" block that includes 755 radicals and components that are used to index Tangut characters in dictionaries of the [[Tangut script]] or to describe the structure of Tangut characters.<ref>{{Cite book | title=The Unicode Standard Version 9.0 | url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode9.0.0/ch18.pdf | page=712 }}</ref>
There is one "Yi Radicals" block that includes 55 radicals used to index Yi characters in dictionaries of the [[Yi script]].<ref>{{Cite book | title=The Unicode Standard Version 6.2 | url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode6.2.0/ch12.pdf | pages=421–422 }}</ref>
Sets of radicals for other [[Chinese family of scripts|sinoform scripts]], such as [[Jurchen script|Jurchen]] and [[Khitan small script]], have also been proposed for encoding in Unicode.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Revised Proposal to Encode the Jurchen Characters in UCS | url=http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n3788.pdf | date=2012-01-26 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title=Final proposal to encode the Khitan Small Script in the SMP of the UCS | url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2016/16245r-n4738r2-khitan-small.pdf | date=2016-09-17 }}</ref>
