! scope="row" | [[Flemish Béguinages]]
| [[File:Leuven-Groot-Begijnhof.jpg|150px|View of the Groot Begijnhof in Leuven, Belgium]]
| {{sort|Flanders|[[Flanders]]}}
| {{sort|13.5|13th century}}
| {{sort|1998|855; 1998; ii, iii, iv (cultural)}}
| ''Béguinage'' ([[French language|French]]) or ''begijnhof'' ([[Dutch language|Dutch]]) are collections of small buildings used by [[Beguine]]s.  These were various lay sisterhoods of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], founded in the 13th century in the [[Low Countries]], comprising religious women who sought to serve God without retiring from the world. The list includes 13 béguinages: [[Ten Wijngaerde (Begijnhof Brugge)|Bruges]], Dendermonde, Diest, Ghent ([[Our-Lady Ter Hooyen|Klein Begijnhof]], [[Groot Begijnhof Sint-Amandsberg|Groot Begijnhof]]), Hoogstraten, Kortrijk, Leuven [[Groot Begijnhof, Leuven|(Groot Begijnhof)]], Lier, Mechelen (Groot Begijnhof), Sint-Truiden, Tongeren and Turnhout.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/855|title=Flemish Béguinages|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref> 
