| {{sort|1695|1695-1699}}
| {{sort|1998|857; 1998; ii, iv (cultural)}}
| The Grand Place is the central square of [[Brussels]]. It is surrounded by guildhalls, the [[Brussels Town Hall|city's Town Hall]], and the Breadhouse. The square is the most important tourist destination and most memorable landmark in Brussels. It measures {{convert|68|by|110|m|ft}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/857|title=La Grand-Place, Brussels|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Major Mining Sites of Wallonia]]
| [[File:Bois du Cazier 2.jpg|150px|View over the Bois du Cazier mine]]
| {{sort|Wallonia|[[Wallonia]]}}
| {{sort|19.5|19th to 20th centuries}}
| {{sort|2012|1344; 2012; ii, iv (cultural)}}
| During the [[Industrial Revolution]] in the 19th century, mining and the heavy industry that relied on coal formed a major part of Belgium's economy. Most of this mining and industry took place in the ''[[sillon industriel]]'' ("industrial valley" in French), a strip of land running across the country where many of the largest cities in Wallonia are located. The named locations of this World Heritage Site are all situated in or near the area of the ''sillon industriel''. Mining activities in the area declined during the 20th century, and today the four mines listed are no longer operational. Nowadays they are each open to visitors as museums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1344|title=Major Mining Sites of Wallonia|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Major Town Houses of the Architect Victor Horta]]
| [[File:Tassel House stairway.JPG|150px|Internal staircase of the Tassel House, Brussels]]
| {{sort|Brussels, Brussels, Saint-Gilles|[[Brussels]] and [[Saint-Gilles, Belgium|Saint-Gilles]], Brussels-Capital}}
| {{sort|19.5|19th to 20th centuries}}
| {{sort|2000|1005; 2000; i, ii, iv (cultural)}}
| The architect [[Victor Horta]] was well known for creating buildings in the [[Art Nouveau]] style fashionable at the time. Four of his most notable surviving works, [[Hôtel Tassel]], [[Hôtel Solvay]], [[Hôtel van Eetvelde]] and [[Maison & Atelier Horta]], are listed as World Heritage Sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1005|title=Major Town Houses of the Architect Victor Horta (Brussels)|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Neolithic flint mines of Spiennes|Neolithic Flint Mines at Spiennes]]
| [[File:Minières néolithiques de silex - Spiennes (1).jpg|150px|View of the inside of the Spiennes mine]]
| {{sort|Hainaut, Mons|[[Mons]], Hainaut}}
| [[Neolithic]]
| {{sort|2000|1006; 2000; i, iii, iv (cultural)}}
| The Neolithic flint mines at Spiennes are Europe's largest and earliest [[neolithic]] mines, located close to [[Wallonia|Walloon]] village of [[Spiennes]], southeast of [[Mons]]. The mines were active during the mid and late Neolithic (4300–2200 BC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1006|title=Neolithic Flint Mines at Spiennes (Mons)|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Notre-Dame Cathedral in Tournai]]
| [[File:ID57081-CLT-0002-01-Tournai cathédrale-PM 02391.jpg|150px|View of the Cathedral of Tournai]] 
| {{sort|Hainaut, Tournai|[[Tournai]], Hainaut}}
| {{sort|12.5|12th century}}
| {{sort|2000|1009; 2000; ii, iv (cultural)}}
| Notre-Dame Cathedral is a [[Roman Catholic]] church, [[Episcopal see|see]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|Diocese of Tournai]]  in [[Tournai]]. Begun in the 12th century on even older foundations, the building combines the work of three design periods with striking effect, the heavy and severe character of the [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] [[nave]] contrasting remarkably with the Transitional work of the [[transept]] and the fully developed [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] of the choir. The transept is the most distinctive part of the building, with its cluster of five [[bell towers]] and [[apse|apsidal]] (semicircular) ends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1009|title=Notre-Dame Cathedral in Tournai|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Plantin-Moretus House-Workshops-Museum Complex]]
| [[File:Library of Plantin-Moretus Museum in Antwerp.jpg|150px|View of the library of the Plantin-Moretus House Museum]]
| {{sort|Antwerp, Antwerp|[[Antwerp]], Antwerp}}
| {{sort|16.5|16th to 17th centuries}}
| {{sort|2005|1185; 2005; ii, iii, iv, vi (cultural)}}
| The Plantin-Moretus Museum is a museum in [[Antwerp]] about early-modern printing in general and the famous printers [[Christophe Plantin]] and [[Jan Moretus]] in particular. It is located in their former residence and printing establishment, [[Plantin Press]], at the [[Friday Markt, Antwerp|Friday Market]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1185|title=Plantin-Moretus House-Workshops-Museum Complex|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" style="background:#D0E7FF;" | [[Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe]]*
| [[File:20120815 Zonienwoud (6).JPG|150px|20120815 Zonienwoud (6)]]
| {{sort|Brabant|[[Province of Brabant|Brussels-Capital, Flanders and Wallonia]]}}
| {{sort|999|N/A}}
| {{sort|2017|1133; 2017; ix (natural)}}
| The [[Sonian Forest]] is the only Belgian component to the multinational inscription 'Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpatians and Other Regions of Europe'. The list includes 63 beech forests in [[Albania]], [[Austria]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Croatia]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Poland]], [[Romania]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1133|title=Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Stoclet House]]
| [[File:Stoclet Palace Hoffmann Brussels 1911.jpg|150px|Exterior of the Stoclet House]]
| {{sort|Brussels, Woluwe-St-Pierre|[[Woluwe-St-Pierre]], Brussels-Capital}}
| {{sort|1911|1911}}
| {{sort|2009|1298; 2009; i, ii (cultural)}}
| The Stoclet Palace was a private mansion built by architect [[Josef Hoffmann]] between 1905 and 1911 in [[Brussels]], Belgium, for banker and art lover [[Adolphe Stoclet]].<ref>{{cite book| last=Sharp|first=Dennis|title=Twentieth Century Architecture|publisher=Images Publishing Group|location=Mulgrave|year=2002|isbn=1-86470-085-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sQUi8kRKWrMC&pg=PA44|ref=harv}} pp.44</ref> It was one of the most refined and luxurious private houses of the twentieth century<ref>{{cite book|last=Watkin|first=David|title=A History of Western Architecture|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|location=London|year=2005|isbn=1-85669-459-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39T1zElEBrQC&pg=PA548|ref=harv}} pp.548</ref> and was lavishly decorated inside, including works by the artist [[Gustav Klimt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1298|title=Stoclet House|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" style="background:#D0E7FF;" | [[The Architectural Work of Le Corbusier|The Architectural Work of Le Corbusier, an Outstanding Contribution to the Modern Movement]]*
| [[Image:Antwerp Corbusier Maison Guiette 01.jpg|Maison Guiette|150px|View of the Maison Guiette]]
| {{sort|Antwerp, Antwerp|[[Antwerp]], Antwerp}}
| {{sort|1927|1927}}
| {{sort|2016|1321; 2016; i, ii, vi (cultural)}}
| The [[Maison Guiette]] is the Belgian component of the multinational inscription 'The Architectural Work of Le Corbusier, an Outstanding Contribution to the Modern Movement'. The building was listed among 16 other buildings of Le Corbusier in [[Argentina]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[India]], [[Japan]] and [[Switzerland]].<br>Maison Guiette was designed by Swiss-French architect [[Le Corbusier]] in 1926 and it was finished in 1927. It served as the home and workplace of Belgian painter René Guiette. It is the only remaining building designed by Le Corbusier in Belgium. It is also known as Les Peupliers, named after the street where the building is situated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1321|title=The Architectural Work of Le Corbusier, an Outstanding Contribution to the Modern Movement|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|-
! scope="row" | [[Lifts on the old Canal du Centre|The Four Lifts on the Canal du Centre and their Environs, La Louvière and Le Roeulx]]
| [[File:Canal du Centre, l'Ascenseur No. 3.jpg|150px|View of Lift No. 3]]
| {{sort|Hainaut|[[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]]}}
| {{sort|1888-1917|1888-1917}}
| {{sort|1998|856; 1998, iii, iv (cultural)}}
| The lifts on the old Canal du Centre are a series of four hydraulic [[boat lift]]s near the town of [[La Louvière]] in the [[Sillon industriel]] of [[Wallonia]]. Along a particular {{convert|7|km|abbr=on}} stretch of the [[Canal du Centre (Belgium)|Canal du Centre]], which connects the river basins of the [[Meuse (river)|Meuse]] and the [[Scheldt]], the water level rises by {{convert|66.2|m}}. To overcome this difference, the 15.4-metre lift at [[Houdeng-Goegnies]] was opened in 1888, and the other three lifts, each with a {{convert|16.93|m}} rise, opened in 1917.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/856|title=The Four Lifts on the Canal du Centre and their Environs, La Louvière and Le Roeulx (Hainaut)|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>
|}

==Tentative list==
In addition to the sites inscribed on the World Heritage list, member states can maintain a list of tentative sites that they may consider for nomination. Nominations for the World Heritage list are only accepted if the site was previously listed on the tentative list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/|title=Tentative Lists|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=7 October 2010}}</ref> As of 2017, Belgium lists 16 properties on its tentative list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/state=be|title=Tentative List – Belgium|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|work=unesco.org|accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>

